input: Good afternoon, champ, how you holding up? Good afternoon, Doctor, I have a lot of lower back pain. Oh no, before we begin, how old are you, sir and which hand do you write with? I'm seventy five now. Right. Great, so tell me, how long have you had this lower back pain? It's been about ten days now. Have your symptoms improved at all since they began? No, they keep getting worse. Does the pain radiate into your legs? Yes, it started radiating down my right leg three days after the lower back pain began, and then the left leg three days after the right. The next day I could barely walk, the pain was so severe. Do you remember the initial date of the beginning of your low back pain? Um, it was on December third nineteen ninety five. Have you seen another doctor for this pain? Yes, I saw my local physician, um, it was on December eleventh, but he wasn't able to pinpoint what was going on. What kind of treatments did he recommend? He gave me some antiinflammatories and sent me on my way. Did you drive yourself? Yes, I did. How did the antiinflammatories work? Um, by the time I got home, I could hardly walk due to the back pain, and I had weakness in my legs. I was, however, able to feed my dogs, and I fixed myself some dinner. Was there any leg numbness? Yes. Since December eleventh. Have you seen an orthopedist for this pain? Yes, I saw one the day after my primary care physician, but my legs gave out and I fell while walking to my car because of the leg weakness and back pain. What kind of imaging studies did that orthopedist do? He did a C T and x rays of my lower back, but he didn't see anything wrong. He recommended I follow up at U I H C. The imaging was on my L S Spine.

- Differential diagnoses: Not provided.
- Clinical impressions: Not explicitly stated.

Plan:
- Follow up at U I H C as recommended by the orthopedist. 
- No specific medications, treatments, or further tests mentioned in the conversation.

Subjective:
- 3 yo F presents with hoarse voice x2-3 days, worsening
- Cough x4 days, mostly resolved, dry, no sputum production, hemoptysis or colored sputum
- Sore throat x2-3 days
- No known sick contacts
- Tried salt water gargles without improvement
- Symptoms constant, hoarseness worsening
- Denies SOB, wheezing, chest pain, fever, headache, N/V, rhinorrhea, congestion, fatigue
- Mild decrease in appetite but still eating and drinking normally
- No changes in BMs or urinary symptoms
- Sleeping well
- No recent travel, exposure to fumes, dust, animals
- No previous similar episodes

PMHx:
- Seasonal allergies
- No other medical conditions or surgeries
- No medications except multivitamins

FHx:
- Paternal uncle dx with colon cancer at age 45
- No family history of lung or heart conditions

SocHx:
- Lives at home with parents and younger sibling
- No smokers in the household
- Meeting developmental milestones

Objective:
- Inspection of throat: mild erythema, no discharge

Assessment:
- Likely viral laryngitis

Plan:
- Will perform full physical exam including inspection of pharynx for erythema, edema, exudates
- Likely viral and should resolve spontaneously within 1-2 weeks
- Advise voice rest
- If suggestive of bacterial infection, will treat with antibiotics
- Follow up if no improvement or worsening symptoms

Subjective:
- Presenting with shortness of breath for 2 weeks, worsening cough for 3 weeks
- Cough: productive with green sputum for 2 weeks, constant
- Shortness of breath: worse with exertion, cold air; present at rest; lasts 5-10 minutes when severe before returning to baseline
- Chest tightness/pain: aching, throbbing; localized to chest
- Denies: fevers, chills, hemoptysis, dizziness, syncope, diaphoresis, confusion, palpitations, headache, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, significant weight loss, appetite changes, dust/fume/irritant exposure
- Mild lower extremity edema
- Mild orthopnea
- Fatigue
- Dyspnea worsens when supine, improves with position changes

PMHx:
- COPD (diagnosed 7 years ago)
- CHF (diagnosed 2 years ago)
- Hospitalized 2 years ago for shortness of breath and hypoxemia, diagnosed with CHF

Medications:
- ACE inhibitor
- Spironolactone
- LABA inhaler
- SABA inhaler - increased use, using almost daily, provides some relief

SocHx:
- Former smoker (quit 2 years ago)
- Drinks alcohol once weekly
- Smokes marijuana (1 joint/week) obtained from medical dispensary

Objective:
- Increased work of breathing

Assessment:
- Likely COPD exacerbation
- Possible bacterial infection given green sputum production

Plan:
- CXR
- Labs
- Ventolin in ED
- Consider steroids
- May require admission for COPD exacerbation management and CHF optimization
- Adjust medications as needed

Guest_family: She has dementia, most of the time she doesn't even remember me. Oh, okay.How old is she? Guest_family: She is eighty three. She also has a history of stroke after which she developed this condition where she knows what she wants to speak but is unable to make the word or sentence. Oh, I see. She has expressive aphasia, correct? Guest_family: Yes, that. Okay, let me check her. She does have a droop to her right side of the face. Ma'am, do you feel any weakness on the right side of your body? Guest_family: She says yes. She had her C T scan earlier today and I have the report. It does not show any acute attack or anything. Guest_family: Thank you.
